<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-07-16T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-07-16T12:00:00-05:00" n="173" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d173">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/8793: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi>
                                    (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bingham</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-07-16T18:00:00+01:00">July 16, 1937—6
                                    p.m.</date><lb/>[Received July 16—12:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>479. Your No. 298, July 14, 7 p.m.,<note n="24" xml:id="d173fn24">Not
                                    printed.</note> referring to the British Ambassador’s
                                conversations with you, Cadogan stated today that he had no
                                additional information and that he felt his Government had done all
                                it could at least for the moment.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Bingham</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>